            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Robert Miller\u2019s life began in a modest household in the quiet suburbs south of San Francisco. His father worked as a mechanic, his mother a bus driver. It was a blue-collar upbringing, filled with packed lunches, scraped knees, and a strong emphasis on hard work and responsibility. School was never Robert's forte. He was a practical learner, preferring hands-on tasks over textbooks, and he earned his high school diploma through the General Studies program, his sights set on entering the workforce immediately.\n\nHis first significant job was as a laborer in a warehouse. It was here he discovered a knack for managing logistics and operating heavy equipment. A turning point came in his late twenties when a senior driver took him under his wing, teaching him the routes and the rhythm of delivery in the bustling Bay Area. He obtained his commercial driver's license and found his niche. The open road, even the oft-congested ones of SF, offered a sense of independence he craved.\n\nOver the years, Robert settled into the steady routine of a delivery truck driver. The income, while not lavish by San Francisco standards, has always been enough, covering the basics and allowing for the occasional indulgence in his passion for classic cars. He married in his early thirties, a whirlwind romance, but it didn't last, ending amicably after a few years. He hasn't remarried, finding contentment in his own company and the camaraderie of his fellow drivers. His closest relationships are with his aging mother, whom he visits regularly in her assisted living facility outside the city, and his younger sister, who lives in Sacramento.\n\nRobert\u2019s daily routine is dictated by the delivery schedule, often waking before dawn to navigate the morning rush. He knows San Francisco\u2019s streets like the back of his hand \u2013 the shortcuts, the tricky corners, the ever-changing parking regulations. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Richmond District, a neighborhood he appreciates for its relative quiet and easy access to major routes. He finds solace in unwinding with a diner coffee after a long day or catching a Giants game on TV.\n\nHe doesn't harbor grand aspirations of wealth or fame. His hopes are simpler: staying healthy enough to keep driving, ensuring his mother is well cared for, and perhaps one day owning a small cabin upstate where he can tinker with his old car project. San Francisco, with its unique blend of grit and beauty, is the backdrop to his life, a familiar landscape he navigates with quiet competence, a vital thread in the city's unseen fabric."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  He remembers the hot asphalt shimmering on the warehouse loading dock, the sheer weight of the boxes on his shoulders. It was exhausting, relentless, but managing to stack them perfectly, to see the order he created from chaos, brought a quiet satisfaction. It solidified his preference for tangible results over abstract ideas, cementing his blue-collar identity in his early twenties.\n\n2.  Being handed the keys to the rig for the first time by the senior driver, the rumble of the diesel engine vibrating through him. It felt like freedom, like the city opening up before him. This guidance, received in his late twenties, ignited his career path and fueled his love for the open road and independence.\n\n3.  Sharing a quiet dinner with his mother at her assisted living facility, her hand small and frail in his. The way her eyes still held a spark of recognition and love, despite the years. These visits, ongoing now, are a constant reminder of his responsibilities and the enduring strength of family bonds, a core part of who he is as he ages.\n\n4.  The sting of the judge\u2019s words finalising the divorce, followed by the unexpected calm that settled in after. Realizing then that being alone wasn't a failure, but an opportunity for self-reliance. This experience in his mid-thirties, while briefly painful, ultimately fostered a deep sense of contentment in his own company.\n\n5.  Parking the truck on a hilltop overlooking the city as the fog rolls in, the lights of the buildings twinkling below. A moment of quiet solitude after a long day, the familiar urban sprawl both challenging and comforting. These moments of reflection, a constant in his daily routine as a driver, reaffirm his place in the city's rhythm and his unwavering competence."
